04681nam a22005415i 9780520909939DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t19911991cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209099397 a10.1525/97805209099392doi  a(DE-B1597)521039  a(OCoLC)44965634  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aRC450.F7D68 1991eb 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a616.89/00944/090341 aDowbiggin, Ian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInheriting Madness :bProfessionalization and Psychiatric Knowledge in Nineteenth-Century France /cIan Dowbiggin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1991] 4cÂ©1991  a1 online resource (227 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMedicine and Society ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. The State of Psychiatric Practice and Knowledge in the Nineteenth Century -- tChapter Two. Francois Leuret and Medical Opposition to Moral Treatment, 1835-1850 -- tChapter Three. Jacques Moreau de Tours and the Crisis of Somaticism in French Psychiatry, 1840-1860 -- tChapter Four. Alienism and the Psychiatric Search for a Professional Identity: The Societe medicopsychologique, 1840-1870 -- tChapter Five. French Alienism and Antipsychiatry, 1860-1900 -- tChapter Six. Hereditarianism, the Clinic, and Psychiatric Practice in Nineteenth-Century France -- tChapter Seven. Science, Politics, and Psychiatric Hereditarianism in the Nineteenth Century -- tConclusion. The Social History of Psychiatric Knowledge -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistorically, one of the recurring arguments in psychiatry has been that heredity is the root cause of mental illness. In Inheriting Madness, Ian Dowbiggin traces the rise in popularity of hereditarianism in France during the second half of the nineteenth century to illuminate the nature and evolution of psychiatry during this period.In Dowbiggin's mind, this fondness for hereditarianism stemmed from the need to reconcile two counteracting factors. On the one hand, psychiatrists were attempting to expand their power and privileges by excluding other groups from the treatment of the mentally ill. On the other hand, medicine's failure to effectively diagnose, cure, and understand the causes of madness made it extremely difficult for psychiatrists to justify such an expansion. These two factors, Dowbiggin argues, shaped the way psychiatrists thought about insanity, encouraging them to adopt hereditarian ideas, such as the degeneracy theory, to explain why psychiatry had failed to meet expectations. Hereditarian theories, in turn, provided evidence of the need for psychiatrists to assume more authority, resources, and cultural influence.Inheriting Madness is a forceful reminder that psychiatric notions are deeply rooted in the social, political, and cultural history of the profession itself. At a time when genetic interpretations of mental disease are again in vogue, Dowbiggin demonstrates that these views are far from unprecedented, and that in fact they share remarkable similarities with earlier theories. A familiarity with the history of the psychiatric profession compels the author to ask whether or not public faith in it is warranted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMental illnessxHistoryx19th centuryxFrancexFrance. 0aMental illnesszFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aPsychiatryxHistoryx19th centuryxFrance. 0aPsychiatryzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press eBook Package Archivez978311063534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520909939423Coveruhttps://w